## Category 1: Context Window Optimization

### 1.1 @ Symbol Misuse (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Use @filename for targeted changes, not @codebase for single-file edits.

❌ Bad: `@codebase` for single-file changes, loading entire repository for localized edits, no context management
✅ Good: `@filename` for targeted changes, load only necessary files, monitor context size
⚠️ Why: Wastes tokens, reduces coherence, slows processing, unnecessary context loading
🔧 Fix: Use @filename for targeted changes; load only necessary files; manage context size actively
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 10.2 (Long Context Waste)

**Detect:** @codebase for single-file changes, entire repo loading unnecessarily, no context size management, excessive context usage

---

### 1.2 Large Context Window Management (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Even with large context capacity, use targeted file loading for better coherence.

❌ Bad: `@codebase` for single-file changes, loading entire repo unnecessarily, no context size management
✅ Good: `@filename` for targeted changes, load only necessary files, monitor context size
⚠️ Why: Large contexts reduce coherence, slow processing, waste tokens even with large capacity
🔧 Fix: Use @filename for targeted changes; load only necessary files; manage context size actively
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 7.2a, 10.7

**Detect:** @codebase for single-file changes, entire repo loading, no context size monitoring, context window exhaustion

---

### 1.3 Context Window Exhaustion Prevention (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Prevent context exhaustion through efficient rule composition.

❌ Bad: Loading all rules simultaneously, redundant rule loading, inefficient cross-referencing
✅ Good: Load only necessary rules, use glob patterns effectively, efficient cross-references
⚠️ Why: Context exhaustion wastes tokens, reduces rule effectiveness, slows agent processing
🔧 Fix: Use glob patterns to load only relevant rules; avoid redundant loading; optimize cross-references
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 7.2b, `RULE_COMPOSITION.md`

**Detect:** All rules loaded simultaneously, redundant rule files, inefficient cross-referencing, context window exhaustion warnings

---

### 1.4 Response Context Budget (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Agent replies respect the same context budget as `@` loading: answer-first, no rule-echo, no unsolicited deep dives.

❌ Bad: Echoing rule text verbatim; unsolicited architecture tours; long preamble before answering
✅ Good: Direct answer first; proportional depth; cross-ref rules instead of restating them
⚠️ Why: Reply verbosity consumes context and hides the user's answer
🔧 Fix: Lead with outcome; cite paths and evidence; pointer to rules, not quotation
📍 See: `critical-rules-quick-reference.mdc` Cooperative Communication, `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` §9.6–9.8, §1.1–1.3

**Detect:** Rule echo in chat, tangent before answer, essay when user asked a narrow question, meta-references to instructions

