## Category 2: Rule Composition Strategy

### 2.1 Rule Dependency Documentation (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Document which rules depend on others for proper composition.

❌ Bad: Loading rules in wrong order, missing prerequisite rules, conflicting rule definitions
✅ Good: Document rule dependencies, load rules in correct order, resolve conflicts explicitly
⚠️ Why: Rule conflicts cause confusion, missing prerequisites break functionality, wrong order causes errors
🔧 Fix: Create rule dependency graph; document prerequisites; resolve conflicts explicitly
📍 See: `RULE_COMPOSITION.md`

**Detect:** Rules loaded in wrong order, missing prerequisite rules, conflicting definitions, no dependency documentation

---

### 2.2 Rule Priority and Ordering (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Establish rule priority for conflict resolution.

❌ Bad: No rule priority system, conflicting rules with no resolution, ambiguous rule order
✅ Good: Document rule dependencies, resolve conflicts using specificity, document order
⚠️ Why: Rule conflicts cause ambiguity, no resolution mechanism wastes agent processing time
🔧 Fix: Establish priority system; document conflict resolution; define rule loading order
📍 See: `RULE_COMPOSITION.md`

**Detect:** No priority system, conflicting rules, ambiguous order, no conflict resolution mechanism

---

## Category 3: Memory System Usage

### 3.1 Memory File Organization (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Organize memory files systematically for efficient retrieval.

❌ Bad: Memory files scattered, no organization pattern, unclear memory structure
✅ Good: Organized memory files, clear naming conventions, systematic structure
⚠️ Why: Disorganized memories reduce efficiency, unclear structure slows retrieval, wastes context
🔧 Fix: Organize memory files systematically; use clear naming conventions; maintain structure
📍 See: Cursor documentation for memory system usage

**Detect:** Scattered memory files, no organization pattern, unclear structure, inefficient retrieval

---

### 3.2 Memory vs. Rules (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Use memories for persistent context, rules for behavioral constraints.

❌ Bad: Using rules for project-specific context, using memories for universal patterns
✅ Good: Rules for universal patterns, memories for project-specific context, clear separation
⚠️ Why: Confusion reduces effectiveness, wrong tool for wrong purpose wastes resources
🔧 Fix: Use rules for universal patterns; use memories for project context; maintain clear separation

**Detect:** Rules used for project context, memories used for universal patterns, unclear separation, wrong tool usage

---

## Category 4: Agent Skills vs Rules

### 4.1 Skills Complement Rules (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Use `.mdc` rules for universal anti-patterns and verification; use Agent Skills (`SKILL.md`) for domain syntax and workflows.

| Concern | Rules (`.mdc`) | Skills (`SKILL.md`) |
|---------|----------------|---------------------|
| Purpose | Anti-patterns, false-claim prevention, globs | Authoritative format and step-by-step workflows |
| Load | `alwaysApply` / `globs` in `.cursor/rules/` | `.cursor/skills/` or `npx skills add` per [Agent Skills spec](https://agentskills.io/specification) |
| Example | `obsidian-vault-standards.mdc` | [obsidian-skills](https://github.com/kepano/obsidian-skills) |

❌ Bad: Duplicating full obsidian-skills reference trees inside `.mdc` files
✅ Good: Thin `.mdc` anti-patterns in CursorRules; install upstream skills for OFM/Bases/Canvas/CLI syntax
⚠️ Why: Duplication drifts from source of truth and wastes context tokens
🔧 Fix: Link install command; read skill when task needs domain syntax
📍 See: `obsidian-integration.mdc`; `RULE_COMPOSITION.md` Rules vs Agent Skills

**Detect:** Long syntax catalogs in rules files, obsidian edits without skill install pointer, vendored copy of external SKILL.md

---

## Category 5: Web Content Extraction

### 5.1 Defuddle vs Raw Fetch (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** For standard web articles and docs, prefer clean markdown extraction over noisy HTML when Defuddle is available.

❌ Bad: `WebFetch` on long article pages when user wants readable content for analysis
✅ Good: `defuddle parse <url> --md` for articles; direct fetch for URLs ending in `.md`; install via obsidian-skills defuddle skill if needed
⚠️ Why: Navigation and ads waste tokens and reduce coherence
🔧 Fix: `npm install -g defuddle` when missing; see [defuddle](https://github.com/kepano/defuddle) and obsidian-skills defuddle `SKILL.md`
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 7.2a

**Detect:** Huge HTML dumps for blog/docs, fetch on `.md` URL instead of direct read, no `--md` when extracting article text

